Plant Sale Announced, Better Than Expected.Strategic Review: Stay the Course.

Green Plains announced the sale of its Obion, TN ethanol Plant to POET, a privately-held biofuel company for $190m ($1.58/gal). The sale is expected to close in 3Q25, and proceeds will be used to reduce debt. The company also announced the completion of its strategic review, and does not intend to alter its current growth strategy.

**Asset** **Sale** **Announced:** Green Plains announced the sale of its Obion, TN ethanol plant to a privately held bio-ethanol company for $190m. This plant had a capacity of 120m gallons of ethanol,and also produces ultra-high protein. This sale follows several non-core asset sales that were announced since the beginning of the year as the company looks to increase focus on its core business. Proceeds from this sale will be used to reduce debt. Green Plains also recently file an S-3 registration, but currently does not have plans to issue securities.

**Strategy** **Unchanged:** The company also announced that the conclusion of the strategic review that began in February 2024. No meaningful changes will be made to the current growth strategy. The company will continue to focus on strengthening its core business. With the sale of the Obion plant the company will have ~770m gallons of ethanol capacity, ~2m tons in dried distiller grains, ~330m lbs of renewable corn oil capacity, ~1.2m tons of CO2 removal capacity (with 830k tons beginning in 4Q25), ~330k tons of UHP annual capacity, and ~169m lbs of CST capacity. The Nebraska CCS project remains on track for a 4Q25 start-up, and is expected to contribute ~$110m in annualized run-rate EBITDA by YE25. By 2026, Green Plains forecasts >$150m in annualized run-rate EBITDA from its decarbonization strategy.

Based in Omaha, Nebraska, Green Plains is a roughly \(3bn\) (in sales) vertically integrated producer and distributor of ethanol. Green Plains operates throughout the Midwest and is the third largest producer of ethanol in the United States producing \(\sim 1.5bn\) gpy.

Our 12- month price target of \(10\) implies 5x 2027E EBITDA, and is supported by a probability- weighted average valuation framework. GPRE faces several risk factors, including: 1) volatility in gasoline demand and price points; 2) corn supply and price dynamics; 3) shifts in the RFS; 4) potential competition from Brazilian ethanol if corn/ sugar ratios shift; 5) diversification M&A; and 6) competitor discipline.
